Description: Fragment of a seal-impression, the fine brown Nile clay has some mica inclusions and was hardened after excavation. The rear shows a concave impression of wood, possibly from a bold or know of a box or similar with three turned string impressions perpendicular to the wood. The side shows finger impressions. The top bears parts traces of one or more seal-impressions. At the top an seal-impression with a circumferential line. In the upper part a decorative curved element with partitioned into several segments by parallel vertical lines. Underneath a small standing baboon with hands raised in a gesture of adoration, to the right of it a disturbed area. Underneath this impression what looks like a second impression of either the same or a different seal, showing the top part preserved with a very small mn-sign (Y7) and a small sun-disc to the right of it.
Findspot: Excavated/Findspot: Amara West (Nubia), E14.7 temple magazine
Acquisition notes: Formerly housed by the Birmingham Museum and Art Gallery and the EES London.
